+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Intel Updates Compilers For Multicore CPUs                         |
|   from the what-about-gcc dept.                                    |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday June 05, @15:46 (Intel)             |
|   http://developers.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/05/1922250   |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Threaded writes with news from Ars that [0]Intel has announced major
updates to its C++ and Fortran tools. The new compilers are Intel's first
that are capable of doing thread-level optimization and
auto-vectorization simultaneously in a single pass. "On the data
parallelism side, the Intel C++ Compiler and Fortran Professional
Editions both sport improved auto-vectorization features that can target
Intel's new SSE4 extensions. For thread-level parallelism, the compilers
support the use of Intel's Thread Building Blocks for automatic
thread-level optimization that takes place simultaneously with
auto-vectorization... Intel is encouraging the widespread use of its
Intel Threading Tools as an interface to its multicore processors. As the
company raises the core count with each generation of new products, it
will get harder and harder for programmers to manage the complexity
associated with all of that available parallelism. So the Thread Building
Blocks are Intel's attempt to insert a stable layer of abstraction
between the programmer and the processor so that code scales less
painfully with the number of cores."

Discuss this story at:
    http://developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/05/1922250

Links:
    0. http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20070605-intel-updates-compilers-for-multicore-era.html


